From b89f23e7ba6733bfa7ecf0298d624d45edf90a20 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Keno Fischer <keno@juliahub.com>
Date: Thu, 16 Jul 2026 08:22:52 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 7/8] sched/membarrier: Add
 MEMBARRIER_CMD_SHARED_EXPEDITED_RSEQ

Cookie based robust futexes with per lock reservation counters require a
quiescing operation on counter epoch changes: before cookie values from a
previous epoch can be reused, all lock attempts holding stale
reservations must be forced to restart. Reservations are only held inside
RSEQ critical sections (respectively inside the VDSO robust cmpxchg
window), so an RSEQ fence of every task which can possibly hold a
reservation for the lock does the job. For PROCESS_SHARED locks these
tasks can belong to arbitrary processes which share nothing but the
memory containing the lock, so neither MEMBARRIER_CMD_PRIVATE_* (own mm
only) nor MEMBARRIER_CMD_GLOBAL_EXPEDITED (no RSEQ semantics) can be
used.

Add MEMBARRIER_CMD_SHARED_EXPEDITED_RSEQ, which executes an RSEQ fence on
all running tasks of all processes which have a shared writable mapping
of the page containing a given user space address. The address is handed
in through a new fourth system call argument, which is ignored by all
other commands. Adding an argument follows the precedent of the cpu_id
argument added in commit 2a36ab717e8f ("rseq/membarrier: Add
MEMBARRIER_CMD_PRIVATE_EXPEDITED_RSEQ").

Targeting is doubly gated:

 1) Only processes which declared their intent to participate via the
    accompanying MEMBARRIER_CMD_REGISTER_SHARED_EXPEDITED_RSEQ
    registration are eligible, following the opt-in philosophy of the
    other expedited commands. A process which registers agrees to both
    issue and receive shared RSEQ fences.

 2) Only processes which have the page mapped shared and writable are
    eligible. Processes which mutually grant write access to shared
    memory already trust each other with much worse than a spurious
    RSEQ restart. The caller itself must have such a mapping of the
    page as well, which prevents fencing arbitrary read only mapped
    files.

The implementation pins the page through the caller's mapping, snapshots
each online CPU's current mm with the usual expedited membarrier
ordering, and then walks the rmap of the pinned folio to collect the
CPUs which currently run tasks of eligible mms. The walk is restricted
to the addressed base page: the rmap visits every VMA mapping any page
of the folio, and on a multi page folio a process mapping only other
pages of it must not be targeted. Because the VMA count is user space
controlled and the walk runs under the global membarrier serialization,
the CPU snapshot is sorted by mm once and each VMA does a binary search
instead of a linear scan of all online CPUs, bounding the critical
section to O((VMAs + CPUs) log CPUs). The collected CPUs get the same
RSEQ IPI as MEMBARRIER_CMD_PRIVATE_EXPEDITED_RSEQ; tasks which are not
running receive their RSEQ event naturally through the scheduler before
they can resume user space execution.

The mm snapshot is compared by pointer after the RCU section ends, so a
stale pointer can cause a spurious RSEQ IPI on a CPU which was
reallocated meanwhile. That is harmless: a fresh task on that CPU went
through the scheduler, which implies the event and barriers anyway.

The eligibility test reads mm->membarrier_state directly during the rmap
walk, so unlike the other registrations no runqueue state
synchronization is required. Registration is a single atomic_or()
publishing the READY bit, followed by a full barrier: without the
barrier, a memory access following the syscall return (the start of an
RSEQ protected sequence) could be performed before READY is visible, and
a concurrent fence which does not observe READY would incorrectly skip a
task whose sequence already started. The barrier pairs with the smp_mb()
at the beginning of membarrier_shared_expedited_rseq(), resolving the
store-buffering case; the pairing is captured in an LKMM litmus test
(verified Never with herd7 against tools/memory-model, and Sometimes
when the barrier is removed).

This series was developed with the assistance of Claude (an AI
assistant by Anthropic); the author reviewed, validated and takes
responsibility for the changes.

